'''''Coruscant Nights II: Street of Shadows''''' is the second installment of the [[Star Wars: Coruscant Nights|''Coruscant Nights'' trilogy]] by [[Michael Reaves]]. It was released on [[August 26]], [[2008]]. Before the final title, the book was to be called ''Chiaroscuro'' and later ''Sins of the Father''. A preview of the book was published in ''[[Coruscant Nights I: Jedi Twilight]]''.

==Publisher's summary==
'''With the Jedi all but wiped out in the grim aftermath of Order 66, the Empire's power seems unchecked. But one lone Knight continues to fight the good fight &mdash; against all odds and when all else fails.'''

''Deep in the bowels of Coruscant, Jedi Jax Pavan seekes out a living as a private investigator; a go-to, can-do guy for the downtrodden. Now a mysterious Zeltron knockout named Deejah approaches Jax with a case that needs to be cracked: to find out who killed her artist lover Volette, brutally murdered hours after his triumphant unveiling of a dazzling new light sculpture with obvious links to lightsaber pyrotechnics.''

''Finding Volette's killer won't be easy &mdash; too many secrets, too many suspects, and all kinds of motives. But with the droid I-5YQ's help, and ex-reporter Den Dhur's excellent snooping skills, the investigation is soon operating like a well-oiled machine.''

''Unfortunately, there's a far more efficient machine hunting Jax. It's a deadly game of cat-and-mouse as the clock starts ticking toward the final explosive showdown&hellip; to see who strikes first and who will die first.''

==Plot summary==
The novel starts off in [[19 BBY/Legends|19 BBY]] on [[Naboo/Legends|Naboo]] where [[Gregar Typho/Legends|Gregar Typho]], who was once the late [[Padmé Amidala/Legends|Padmé Amidala's]] [[Bodyguard/Legends|bodyguard]], is visiting her [[Burial/Legends|grave]]. The narrative reveals that he loved Padmé deeply, and vows that he will find and track down her killer, thus avenging her [[Death/Legends|death]].

Skipping over some time after [[Coruscant Nights I: Jedi Twilight|the previous novel]], [[Jax Pavan]], [[Laranth Tarak]], [[Den Dhur]], [[I-5YQ]] and [[Haninum Tyk Rhinann]] are living as [[Private investigator/Legends|private investigators]] in the bowels of [[Coruscant/Legends|Imperial Center]]. They come across a new case when they are encountered by [[Dejah Duare]] where she leads the party to her apartment to find her partner, [[Ves Volette]], has been murdered.

[[The Force/Legends|Force]]-using [[Bounty hunter/Legends|bounty hunter]] [[Aurra Sing/Legends|Aurra Sing]] is tasked by [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Darth Vader]] to go to Imperial Center to hunt down Jax.

During their investigation to Ves Volette's murder, Jax and I-Five work out that Volette was killed by an [[Umber 3PO unit]] owned by a [[Vlaçan Umber|wealthy family]] who purchased Volette's artworks. The 3PO unit [[Self-destruct mechanism/Legends|destroys itself]] so that its masters won't suffer. The reasoning for the droid's murder of Volette was because it was worried that the [[Caamasi/Legends|Caamasi]] (Volette) was having an affair with the [[Kirma Umber|wealthy woman]], and thus, might destroy the [[Marriage/Legends|marriage]] between the family. This raises something to I-Five about [[Sentience/Legends|sentience]], which he wants to achieve, because this [[Droid/Legends|droid]] went beyond its [[Protocol droid/Legends|protocol]] to defend its masters' honor.

Gregar Typho learns that Darth Vader was somehow responsible for Padmé's murder, along with the "death" of [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker]]. So he decides to kill Vader on Imperial Center in order to avenge her death. But Vader catches Typho off guard and asks why he was [[Hunting/Legends|hunting]] him. Typho reveals about his wanting to avenge Padmé, and, to a lesser degree, Anakin. Vader confirms of his murder of Padmé and Anakin, and [[Telekinesis/Legends|Force-chokes]] Typho to death. But Typho died knowing that he somehow hurt Vader more than killing him would have ever done to avenge Padmé.

With the case of her partner's murder solved, Dejah Duare decides to leave Imperial Center for her home, accompanied by Jax and his party. But they are attacked by Aurra Sing. Jax and Sing fight, and Sing is defeated, if not killed (later sources reveal that Sing may have survived her duel with Jax). Because of the Jax-Sing fight, Dejah decides to stay with him. This prompts Laranth, who Den knows loves Jax, to leave the group, with Dejah replacing Laranth in the position.

The novel ends with Rhinann plotting to leave Jax's group and regain favor with Vader.

==Continuity==
True to the pulp noir roots celebrated in the [[Star Wars: Coruscant Nights|''Coruscant Nights'']] series, ''Street of Shadows'' had several essential ingredients of a murder mystery: an alluring [[Zeltron/Legends|Zeltronian]] [[Gender/Legends|female]] and an expository “parlor scene” where the [[Private investigator/Legends|investigator]] calls out the true [[Assassin/Legends|killer]]. And sure enough, the butler ([[Droid/Legends|droid]]) did it. ''Street of Shadows'' was, thus far, the only story that included the [[Caamas Firestorm|destruction of Caamas]] as a contemporaneous event in its plot, though the event was introduced as part of [[The galaxy/Legends|galactic]] history in [[Timothy Zahn]]’s ''[[Specter of the Past]]'' ([[1997]]).<ref name="ERC" />

[[Gregar Typho/Legends|Typho’s]] first name, Gregar, was not mentioned in this book, though he was given it in [[The Last of the Jedi: Death on Naboo|''Death on Naboo'']] ([[2006]]). Given the chronological placement of both works, it’s possible that [[Malorum]]’s investigation into [[Padmé Amidala/Legends|Padmé’s]] demise in ''Death on Naboo'' renewed or further fueled Typho’s quest in ''Street if Shadows''. The novel erroneously suggested, through Typho’s recollections, that Padmé’s [[Death/Legends|death]] had occurred before [[Palpatine/Legends|Palpatine]] declared himself [[Emperor/Legends|Emperor]], though the movie [[Star Wars: Episode III Revenge of the Sith|''Revenge of the Sith'']] had Typho seated next to a very-much-alive Padmé at that exact moment.<ref name="ERC" />

Dejah's name is misspelled as "Deejah" on the back of ''Coruscant Nights II: Street of Shadows'', but "Dejah" throughout the book.

At the end of Chapter 8, Rhinann comes across a record dated nearly twenty years ago, which the novel mentions as a time during the "waning years of the Clone Wars." The novel takes place in 18.8 BBY, which is only a few months after the end of the Clone Wars. This is presumably an error.

In Chapter 10, Jax is contemplating the fate of any surviving lightsabers. He book mentions his thoughts on Anakin Skywalker's participation in [[Operation: Knightfall/Legends|Operation Knightfall]], which is something he did not know until later in the series.

Chapter 19 talks about how the Naboo trade embargo was 23 years ago when it was really 14 years ago 

